title: Two-body photodisintegration of 3He and 4He in the delta (1236) region.

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.237, p.447 (1975)

x4freetext: Two-body photodisintegration of 3He and 4He in the
delta (1236) region.
600 Mev Saclay linac (ALS).
Deutrons/tritons were analyzed in the focal plane of
the spectrometer using a ladder counter consisting
of four 90 mm x 220 mm x 2 mm plastic scintillators
in coincidence with a large 460 mm x 240 mm x 5 mm
plastic detector.
Protons were detected using telescope consisted of
two 200 mm x 220 mm x 5 mm plastic scintillators.
To extract the good events, a st of conditions was
imposed on the spectra: broad cuts on the
spectrometer pulse-height histogram define the
selected kind of particle (deuteron or triton); then
the time interval histograms for true and random
coincidences associated with these selected events
were established. The number of good events was
defined as the number of events in the peak of the
true coincidence plot, corrected by the average
number of random coincidences read in the delayed
coincidence plot.
The following effects were considered:
- proton absorption in the copper absorber situated
in front of telescope; this correction never
exceeded 15 %;
- counting losses due to the high counting rate in
the telescope scintillators: they were estimated
from the single rates for each run and corrections
were made ranging from 2 - 8 %;
- events originating in the target walls: the
correction amounted to 1.5 % in the worst case.
Only statistical uncertainties are given.
Differential cross sections for the reactions
3He(g,p)d and 4He(g,p)t were measured at proton c.m.
angles of 60 and 90 degree for proton energies
ranging from 150 - 450 MeV with an average resolution
of 8 MeV. Bremsstrahlung was used as a photon source;
deutrons/tritons were analyzed in a magnetic
spectrometer whereas coincident protons were detected
in a plastic scintillator telescope. The experimental
method includes a calibration by means of 1H(g,pi)p
differential cross section measurement at 90 degree
c.m. in the same photon energy range. the 3H and 4He
two-body photodisintegration differential cross
sections show a monotonically decreasing variation
with photon energy. in addition, partial data on the
differential cross section of the reaction
4He(g,n)3He at 90 and 120 degree neutron c.m. angle
are given
Data were compiled at the USA BNL NNDC by
V.V.Varlamov.
Corrected by V. Varlamov: dates, doi,
STATUS, COMMON, ERR-S, lowercase, SUBENT 008 added.
